    seoDesc: "VFX for indie films starts with the right expectations. What visual effects really are, why the best ones are invisible, and the budget mindset that makes them possible. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 1 of VFX on a Budget.",
    dek: `Before you touch a single piece of software, you need the right picture of what visual effects actually are — because the biggest budget on an indie VFX shot isn't money, it's expectation. Get that right and you can do more than you think. Get it wrong and you'll burn weeks chasing a shot that was never going to work.`,
    body: `<p>When most people hear "VFX," they picture spaceships, exploding planets, armies of CGI creatures — the stuff of hundred-million-dollar tentpoles. So the first thing I want to do in this course is shrink that picture down to something useful, because <strong>the vast majority of visual effects work in real films is invisible.</strong> It's a wire removed from a stunt. A modern car erased from a period street. A sky replaced because the day turned grey. A muzzle flash added to a prop gun that never fired. A set that ends ten feet out of frame, extended into a whole city. You've watched thousands of VFX shots in films you'd never call "effects movies," and you never noticed a single one — which is exactly the point. Visual effects, at the indie level, are not about spectacle. They're about <em>solving problems</em> the camera couldn't solve on the day, and doing it so cleanly the audience never suspects there was a problem at all. Once you stop thinking "how do I make something amazing" and start thinking "how do I fix or add this one specific thing," VFX stops being magic and becomes a craft you can actually learn.</p>

<h2>What indie VFX actually covers</h2>

<p>Here's the honest range of what a solo filmmaker or tiny post team can realistically pull off:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Cleanup and removal.</b> Erasing rigs, wires, boom mics, crew reflections, modern signage, logos, and continuity mistakes. This is the bread and butter — and often the most valuable VFX you'll ever do.</li>
  <li><b>Compositing.</b> Combining two or more images into one — a green-screen actor onto a background, a screen replacement on a phone, a comp of separately-shot elements. This is the core skill everything else builds on.</li>
  <li><b>Set extensions.</b> Making a small or unfinished location look bigger or different — extending a wall into a skyline, adding to a landscape, hiding the edge of your set.</li>
  <li><b>Practical-plus effects.</b> Muzzle flashes, blood hits, sparks, breath, small fire and smoke — enhancing or replacing effects that are unsafe, expensive, or impossible to do live.</li>
  <li><b>Simple CG elements.</b> A drone, a distant vehicle, a sign, a title that interacts with the scene. Achievable, but the most time-hungry — and where indies most often bite off more than they can chew.</li>
</ul>

<h2>The one skill that matters most</h2>

<p>If there's a single idea I want you to carry through all twelve chapters, it's this: <strong>the quality of your VFX is decided on set, not in post.</strong> Amateurs think of visual effects as something you "add later" to fix whatever you didn't plan for — and that mindset is why so much indie VFX looks fake. The professionals treat every effects shot as a partnership between what the camera captures and what the computer adds, and they obsess over getting the camera half right: a locked-off tripod instead of a wobbly handheld, even lighting on a green screen, a clean plate shot of the empty background, reference of how the light falls. Do that, and a modest effect drops in convincingly in an afternoon. Skip it, and no amount of software or tutorials will save the shot — you'll spend days fighting a battle you lost before you rolled camera. That's the difference between VFX that serves the story and VFX that pulls the audience straight out of it. Everything in this course is built on that foundation: plan the effect, shoot <em>for</em> the effect, and let post be the easy part. We'll spend the next three chapters entirely on planning and shooting before we ever open a piece of software, because that's where indie films are won or lost. Manage your expectations, pick effects that fit your skill and schedule, and get the camera right — and you'll be amazed how much you can do with almost no money at all.</p>

<div class="pullquote">At the indie level, the best visual effect is the one nobody notices. VFX isn't about spectacle — it's about solving the problem the camera couldn't, so cleanly the audience never knows there was one.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My first real VFX shot was a wire removal on a short — an actor "levitating" a coffee mug on fishing line. I'd shot it handheld, no clean plate, the line crossing a busy patterned background. It took me an entire weekend and still looked bad. The next time I did the exact same effect, I locked the camera on a tripod, shot ten seconds of the empty table as a clean plate, and lit it flat. The removal took twenty minutes and was flawless. Same effect, same software, same skill level — the only thing that changed was what I did on set. That weekend taught me the whole course in one shot.</p>
</div>`,
