    dek: `Every effect you'll ever finish easily was designed before the camera rolled. This chapter is about the unglamorous pre-production work — breaking down the script, listing every effects shot, and deciding how each one gets done — that separates VFX you can actually deliver from VFX that quietly sinks your film.`,
    body: `<p>A big studio has a VFX supervisor on set whose entire job is to make sure every effects shot is captured correctly. On an indie film, <strong>that person is you</strong> — and if you don't do the job in pre-production, nobody will. So before your shoot, sit down with the locked script and read it purely as a VFX hunt: every time the story asks for something the camera can't simply point at and record, flag it. A gunshot. A screen showing a specific video. A window that needs to look out on a different city. A creature, a wire gag, a rainstorm you can't afford, a period street with modern cars in the background. Each of those is a VFX shot, and each one needs a plan long before your shoot day. The goal of this breakdown isn't to scare you — it's to let you make decisions with time on your side: which effects are worth doing, which should be rewritten out of the script, and exactly how each surviving one will be captured so post is straightforward.</p>

<h2>Building your VFX shot list</h2>

<p>For every effect that survives the cut, work out and write down the plan:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>What's the effect?</b> Describe it in one plain sentence: "erase the modern streetlight behind the actor," "add a muzzle flash to the pistol," "replace the laptop screen." Specific beats vague.</li>
  <li><b>How is it achieved?</b> Green screen? Clean-plate removal? Set extension? A separately-shot element composited in? Decide the method now, because the method dictates how you shoot.</li>
  <li><b>What must the camera capture?</b> A locked-off shot? A clean plate of the empty scene? Tracking markers? Reference of the lighting? This is the list that goes on your call sheet.</li>
  <li><b>Who does it, and how long?</b> Be honest about your skills and hours. A five-second CG creature might be forty hours you don't have. A wire removal might be twenty minutes. Budget your time like money.</li>
  <li><b>What's the fallback?</b> If the effect fails, what's plan B? Knowing your fallback keeps a hard shot from holding your whole film hostage.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Design shots to be easy</h2>

<p>Here's where pre-production pays off most: once you know an effect is coming, you can <strong>design the shot to make that effect simple.</strong> This is the difference between amateurs and pros, and it costs nothing but forethought. Need to remove something behind an actor? Lock the camera on a tripod so a clean plate lines up perfectly — a moving camera turns a twenty-minute fix into a multi-day nightmare. Adding a set extension? Frame with a little headroom and keep the horizon steady so the extension has room to sit. Compositing a screen replacement? Put a few small tracking markers at the corners of the monitor and keep it from being blown out or reflective. Doing a green-screen shot? Match the lighting angle and color to the background you'll drop in, and give the actor space from the screen so it doesn't spill green light onto them. None of this is extra gear or extra money — it's just <em>knowing what post needs and giving it to them on the day.</em> The filmmaker who plans gets an effect that drops in clean in an afternoon; the one who "fixes it later" gets weeks of misery and a shot that still looks wrong. Every chapter that follows assumes you've done this planning, because it's the multiplier that makes everything else in the course achievable on no budget. Do the boring breakdown. Build the list. Design each shot for its effect. Your future self, sitting at the computer at 2 a.m., will thank you — and the next chapter drills into the single most important thing that list will tell you to do on set.</p>

<div class="pullquote">On an indie film, you are the VFX supervisor. If the plan for an effect doesn't exist before you roll camera, it doesn't exist — and post becomes a rescue mission instead of the easy part.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I once inherited a short in post where the director wanted every practical prop screen "just replaced later." No markers, handheld camera, screens catching glare — eleven shots of pure pain. On my own next film I did the opposite: taped tiny corner markers on every screen, locked the camera where I could, and shot a clean plate of each. The screen replacements went four times faster and looked twice as good. Same effect. The only difference was thirty seconds of planning per setup on the day. Pre-production is the cheapest VFX budget you'll ever spend.</p>
</div>`,
