    dek: `The tools are not the barrier anymore. Professional-grade VFX software is free or nearly free — the same node-based compositors and 3D suites used on real shows. This chapter maps the landscape so you know what to install, what each program is actually for, and where to start.`,
    body: `<p>A generation ago, the software alone was a barrier that priced out every indie filmmaker — compositing and 3D packages cost more than a used car. That world is gone. Today you can download tools that are genuinely professional, free or for the price of a nice dinner, and do the vast majority of what a budget film needs. So the good news of this chapter is simple: <strong>the software is not your limitation anymore — your time and skill are.</strong> That said, VFX software isn't one program; it's a small toolkit of different tools for different jobs, and the most common beginner mistake is grabbing the wrong one and concluding VFX is "too hard." Compositing (combining images) is a different tool from 3D (building objects), which is different again from your editor. Let me map the landscape so you can install what fits your actual shots and ignore the rest.</p>

<h2>The budget VFX toolkit</h2>

<p>Here's what does the heavy lifting, and what each is for:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>DaVinci Resolve (free) — Fusion page.</b> Resolve is a free editor and color tool, and it has a full node-based compositor, Fusion, built right in. For most indie shots — keying, screen replacement, cleanup, simple comps — this is the best place to start, because it lives inside the tool you're already editing and grading in.</li>
  <li><b>Blender (free) — 3D and compositing.</b> The open-source powerhouse. If you need a 3D object, a set extension, a CG element, motion tracking, or particle effects like fire and smoke, Blender does it all for free. Steeper to learn, but there's nothing you can't do in it.</li>
  <li><b>HitFilm (free tier) — VFX for editors.</b> A friendly editor-plus-VFX hybrid with lots of built-in effects (muzzle flashes, lightning, particles) aimed squarely at beginners. Great for action-style effects without deep compositing knowledge.</li>
  <li><b>Natron (free) — dedicated compositor.</b> An open-source node compositor similar in spirit to the industry-standard Nuke. Worth knowing if you want to learn "proper" node compositing on a budget.</li>
  <li><b>Cheap paid options.</b> After Effects (subscription) is the industry layer-based compositor with a huge plugin and tutorial ecosystem; Mocha for planar tracking is superb. Worth it later, not required to start.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Where to actually start</h2>

<p>Faced with that list, resist the urge to install everything and master nothing. My advice for almost every filmmaker reading this: <strong>start with DaVinci Resolve and its Fusion page, and only add Blender when a specific shot forces you to.</strong> The reason is workflow — Resolve is already your editor and colorist, so keeping compositing in the same program means no exporting and round-tripping between apps, and the skills you build transfer straight to your edit and grade. The overwhelming majority of budget effects (screen replacements, sky swaps, cleanup, green-screen comps) live comfortably in Fusion, and you'll get further faster by going deep on one capable tool than by dabbling in five. Reach for Blender the day you genuinely need a 3D element or a proper 3D camera track, and reach for HitFilm if your film is action-heavy and you want ready-made muzzle flashes and sparks without building them from scratch. But don't let tool-shopping become procrastination. The pros aren't pros because of their software; they're pros because they've done a thousand shots. Pick your one starting tool, learn its keying and tracking and masking nodes, and put in the reps. With the foundations covered and a tool chosen, the rest of this course gets hands-on — starting with the workhorse of budget VFX, green screen, which is where we head next.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The software stopped being the barrier years ago. What separates convincing indie VFX from amateur VFX isn't the program — it's the reps. Pick one capable free tool and go deep.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>I wasted my first month of learning VFX installing and half-learning four different programs, convinced the "right" one would make it click. It never did — because switching tools every week meant I never got past the tutorials in any of them. Then I forced myself to stay in Resolve's Fusion page for a whole short film, every shot, no exceptions. By the end I could key and track and clean up without thinking. The lesson: depth beats breadth. One tool, many shots, and suddenly VFX isn't intimidating — it's just a Tuesday.</p>
</div>`,
