    dek: `A green screen is only as good as the way you light and shoot it. Get it right on the day and it keys in one click; get it wrong and no software on earth will save you. Here's how to pull a clean, evenly-lit green screen with cheap gear and a small space.`,
    seoTitle: "Shooting Green Screen on a Budget | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Green screen on a budget — how to light, space, and shoot a chroma key cleanly with cheap gear so it composites without a fight. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 5 of VFX on a Budget.",
    body: `<p>Green screen — chroma key — is the workhorse of budget VFX: put an actor in front of a solid green backdrop, then replace the green with any background you like. It's how a filmmaker in a garage puts a character on a rooftop, in a spaceship, or in a location they could never afford to shoot. And here's the truth almost nobody tells beginners: <strong>a clean key is 90% about how you light the green screen and only 10% about the software.</strong> The keyer in Resolve or After Effects is genuinely good — but it can only work with what you give it. Feed it an evenly-lit, wrinkle-free, well-separated green screen and it pulls a perfect key in seconds. Feed it a shadowy, blotchy, wrinkled sheet with green spilling all over your actor's hair, and you'll spend days fighting it and still lose. So this chapter is mostly about the shoot, because that's where the battle is won.</p>

<h2>Lighting and shooting a clean key</h2>

<p>The rules that make a green screen key effortlessly:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Light the screen and the subject separately.</b> This is the golden rule. Use one set of lights for an even green, and a completely different set for your actor. If the same lights hit both, you can't control either.</li>
  <li><b>Even is everything.</b> Aim for a flat, uniform green with no bright spots or shadows. Two soft lights at 45 degrees from each side usually does it. Check for hot spots on a monitor, not by eye.</li>
  <li><b>Distance kills spill.</b> Get your actor as far from the screen as your space allows — six to ten feet if you can. Distance stops green light bouncing onto their skin and hair, which is the number-one cause of ugly edges.</li>
  <li><b>Kill the wrinkles.</b> A wrinkled backdrop makes shadows that break the key. Stretch fabric taut, steam it, or use a painted wall or pop-up muslin. Chroma-key paint on a flat wall is cheap and superb.</li>
  <li><b>Add a backlight.</b> A rim or hair light on your actor separates them from the green and gives the keyer clean edges to grab — hugely helpful on hair.</li>
  <li><b>Match your key light to the plate.</b> Light your actor from the same angle and color as the background you'll composite them into, or the comp will never look real (more on that next chapter).</li>
</ul>

<h2>Cheap gear, professional results</h2>

<p>You do not need a studio for any of this. A collapsible green screen or a few yards of green muslin, or a wall painted with chroma-key green, costs very little. Your lights can be cheap LED panels or even work lights with diffusion — what matters is <em>control and evenness</em>, not wattage or brand. The real budget in green screen isn't money; it's space and care. If you've only got a small room, shoot tighter — a green screen behind a seated actor for a car interior or a computer scene needs far less backdrop than a full-body wide, and tight shots are much more forgiving. Expose the green properly (a good keyer likes it neither crushed dark nor blown out), turn off any auto settings that shift color, and shoot in the highest quality your camera allows, because compression is the enemy of clean edges — if your camera offers it, a higher bit-rate or a less-compressed format makes keying noticeably easier. Do a test key on the day if you possibly can: pull a quick key on set or right after, and if the edges are a mess, you can relight and reshoot while you're still there, instead of discovering the problem weeks later when the set is gone. Green screen has a reputation for looking cheap and fake, but that reputation comes entirely from bad lighting and lazy shooting, not from the technique itself. Light it flat, separate your subject, kill the spill, and you'll pull keys that look every bit as good as the expensive stuff. Now that you've captured a clean key, the next chapter takes it into the computer — pulling the key and compositing your actor into a new world convincingly.</p>

<div class="pullquote">A clean key is 90% lighting and 10% software. The keyer can only work with what you give it — win the battle on set, with even light and distance from the screen, and post becomes one click.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My worst green-screen day was an actor standing right against a wrinkled bedsheet I'd tacked to a wall, lit by the same lights hitting her face. Green everywhere, shadows in the folds, a nightmare key that never looked right. My best was almost embarrassingly easy: chroma-green paint on a flat wall, the actor eight feet in front of it, two soft lights on the wall, two on her, and a rim light behind. I pulled the key in Resolve in about thirty seconds and it was flawless. Same camera, same software — all the difference was in the setup. Green screen isn't hard. Bad green screen is easy; good green screen is just discipline.</p>
</div>`,
